Association Rules for Adventure Work Dataset

Author

Oscar Hernandez Mata 

library(arules)
library(readr)

In this project I wanted to discover relationships in dataset AdventureWorkDW considering whether a costumer could likely be classified as a potential bike buyer or not according to a set of characteristics like ownership of a home, ownership of a car, commute distance, and children at home. Hence, I created a subset of the dataset AdventureWorkDW using the subset function, with the columns: age, number of children at home, income, house owner, educational level, number of cars owned. Then, I converted the data type with as.factor function that arule friendly, that is, factor.

Next, I installed the arules package in Rstudio to build association rules that analyze the data and uncover the relationship between products and costumers. Then, I executed the apriori algorithm and set a minimum support of 0.04, a confidence threshold of 0.7, and as the right-hand side of the rules âBikeBuyer=Buyerâ and âBikeBuyer=Non-buyerâ to explore the association rules related to these two attributes. Finally, I sorted by count and inspected 1:5 using the sorted and inspect functions.

             select = c("MaritalStatus",  "Gender", "YearlyIncome", "TotalChildren", 
                        "NumberChildrenAtHome", "EducationLevel", "Occupation", "HouseOwnerFlag",  
                        "NumberCarsOwned", "FirstPurchaseYearMonth",  "CommuteDistance",  
                        "Region", "AgeRange","BikeBuyer"))

#Convert to data types that are arules friendly

#Execute the Apriori algorithm
#Minimum length is 3
#Minimum support is 0.04
#Minimum confidence is 0.7
oh9_rules<-apriori(oh9_arules_input,
               parameter=list(minlen=3, supp=0.04, conf=0.7),
               appearance=list(rhs=c("BikeBuyer=Non-buyer","BikeBuyer=Buyer"),
               default="lhs"), control=list(verbose=F))
oh9_rules.sorted <-sort(oh9_rules, by="count")
inspect(oh9_rules.sorted[1:5])
